wever, the Israeli military was able to penetrate Egyptian defense lines in=
 the east, cross to the west bank of the canal and besiege the Egyptian Thi=
rd Army in the southern sector of Sinai. The Israelis may well have encircl=
ed the Second Army in northern Sinai had U.S. President Richard Nixon not o=
rdered Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir to agree to a ceasefire. Egyptian =
media continues to describe Sadat as the hero of the Suez Canal crossing.</=
p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">A few years later,=
 Iran and Iraq both claimed victory in the First Gulf War, more commonly kn=
own in the West as the Iran-Iraq War (1980-1988). Iraq referred to the conf=
lict as &quot;Saddam's Qadisiyyah,&quot; a reference to the Battle of Qadis=
iyyah in 636, which enabled the Arabs to conquer Persia, while Iran referre=
d to it as the &quot;Sacred Defense.&quot; The truth is that neither side e=
merged victorious. The war left 1 million dead and inflicted more than $400=
 billion in damage, equivalent to $1.5 trillion today. In August 1990, the =
Iraqi army occupied Kuwait, even though it should have known that the U.S. =
